ese former combatants’ memories of the anti-colonial conflict intertwine with, contradict or coexist alongside the state-sponsored narrative of the war constructed after independence. Making an original contribution to debates about gender, nationalism and memory, this book will appeal to students and scholars of history and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWomen in warzAlgeriaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Africa / North.2bisacsh  aAlgeria.  aDecolonisation.  aGender.  aMemory.  aNation-building.  aNationalism.  aOral History.  aState-building.  aVeterans.1 aVince, Natalya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packagez978311128311140uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978071909883340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780719098833423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780719098833/original  a978-3-11-128311-1  Manchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packageb2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles